The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | Good Morning
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             Good Morning
      Hello It's Wednesday , August 20 , 2008                    
	Whats on    Emergency services like hospitals, blood banks, medicine shops, and hearses will be outside the purview of the bandh.     State and central government departments will be open but employees may not come.     High court and other city courts will officially remain open.     State buses and trams will officially ply depending on employee attendance.    Taxi associations said there is no bar on taxis plying but most may stay off the road.     Metro Railway authorities said they would operate trains according to schedule.     Long-distance and suburban trains will ply provided there is no obstruction on the tracks.     Air-traffic control at the airport would be functional, to aid over-flying flights and for emergency landings.    All 19 markets run by the CMC will be officially open but shopkeepers may stay away.     
	Whats off    IT services will remain within the purview of the bandh.    Private buses and autorickshaws will not ply.     Most of the domestic flights will remain cancelled while most international flights would be rescheduled. Flights scheduled before 6am should operate if the situation permits. Emergency numbers: Air India: 18001801407. Jet: 39893333. Kingfisher:18002093030/1800180010. IndiGo: 18001803838. Deccan: 18004257008.    Educational institutions will not be open.     Most malls and art galleries will be closed.                                                                                                                                                                 
